WEBVTT

00:09.420 --> 00:13.360
Coming up next is the science fiction radio show, so stay with us.

00:29.020 --> 00:34.340
This is the science fiction radio show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.840 --> 00:46.460
And here are your hosts. This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. Sooner or later a true science

00:46.460 --> 00:50.640
fiction fan has to attend a convention. Conventions range from the incredible Worldcon,

00:50.900 --> 00:53.660
a world science fiction convention with thousands of people in attendance,

00:54.060 --> 00:58.080
to small local gatherings with less than a hundred fans. And then there are the conventions in the

00:58.080 --> 01:01.940
middle, big enough to attract first rank authors and have a fascinating dealers room,

01:01.940 --> 01:05.600
but small enough to create a comfortable, intimate atmosphere between guests and fans.

01:06.200 --> 01:10.360
Such a convention is Aggicon, a yearly science fiction gathering held in College Station, Texas.

01:10.820 --> 01:15.560
Aggicon is organized and run by students at Texas A&M University. At the last Aggicon,

01:15.720 --> 01:20.580
number 14, held in the spring of 1983, we spoke with Gordon Lewis, the head of the Aggicon committee.

01:21.040 --> 01:23.540
We asked him to give us a little of the background behind Aggicon.

01:24.180 --> 01:30.060
Aggicon number one, so far as I know, was not originally called Aggicon. It was just called

01:30.060 --> 01:38.160
the Texas A&M science fiction convention or something to that effect. And they just decided

01:38.160 --> 01:43.780
it would be real fun to invite an author down and have a little miniature convention that lasted

01:43.780 --> 01:51.500
two days. And I think they showed three films. I saw a report on Aggicon 4. I think Aggicon 3 was

01:51.500 --> 01:56.640
the first one that was called Aggicon. I saw a report on number four. They took in a total of

01:56.640 --> 02:05.900
$800 and spent $400. And they had two guests and showed six films total. And that was about all

02:05.900 --> 02:11.660
the programming they had. And since then, we have moved onward and upward to better and better

02:11.660 --> 02:18.100
things to where this year we have 30 guests. We're showing eight major films at night. We have

02:18.740 --> 02:25.380
films running all day long. And we have the panels and the readings. And our budget this year is

02:25.380 --> 02:31.380
something like to take in $15,000 and to spend around $14,000 was what was budgeted.

02:48.720 --> 02:53.380
Putting on a major science fiction convention as Aggicon certainly is takes a good deal of work.

02:53.680 --> 02:58.360
The work is done by a committee on the Texas A&M campus called Cepheid Variable. We asked Lewis

02:58.360 --> 03:06.280
what the word Cepheid Variable meant. A Cepheid Variable is a pulsating star which there is one

03:06.280 --> 03:12.720
in the Cephas star system. And if you look at it, it will appear to grow brighter and dimmer and

03:12.720 --> 03:19.620
occasionally to change colors. And that's where we took our name from. What does Cepheid Variable

03:19.620 --> 03:26.320
actually do? Cepheid Variable is a science fiction and fantasy committee. It's out of the student

03:26.320 --> 03:32.860
programs office here on campus. And because we are a committee, we do programming through the

03:32.860 --> 03:39.460
student programs office. Some of the other clubs on campus do their own activities and programming

03:39.460 --> 03:44.620
just for their own members, but we program for the entire university as well as Aggicon,

03:44.860 --> 03:50.260
which is for people who aren't even members of the university. Is Aggicon the only responsibility

03:50.260 --> 03:56.020
of Cepheid Variable? That's our major reason for being. However, we also program all year long.

03:56.140 --> 04:01.420
We show science fiction fantasy films here on campus. And we are a meeting place for science

04:01.420 --> 04:08.000
fiction fantasy fans here on campus. Also, on occasion, we do send delegates to other conventions

04:08.840 --> 04:12.900
within the state as well as outside the state. Usually in the summertime though,

04:12.920 --> 04:18.080
because most of our students are busy during the fall and spring. Lewis says 95% of the

04:18.080 --> 04:23.660
members of Cepheid Variable are students at the university, but not all. We have a few who are

04:23.660 --> 04:30.260
not. Most of them are like we have one former student. We have one person who is laying out

04:30.260 --> 04:34.500
for a few semesters while he works. And that way he can become a Texas resident and not have to

04:34.500 --> 04:41.020
pay out of state tuition. And Becky Matthews, who is one of our guests, we kind of count her as a

04:41.020 --> 04:46.480
member of the convention committee because she was chairman of Aggicon 11 and has helped us

04:46.480 --> 04:51.100
with the roast program this year. Next time we'll talk with Gordon Lewis about the fascinating

04:51.100 --> 05:02.440
attractions Aggicon has to offer. This has been the science fiction radio show,

05:02.440 --> 05:07.060
production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa

05:07.060 --> 05:08.500
College in Odessa, Texas.

05:57.920 --> 06:01.820
Coming up next is the science fiction radio show, so stay with us.

06:17.540 --> 06:22.860
This is the science fiction radio show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:25.440 --> 06:35.000
And here are your hosts. This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Aggicon is one of the best known

06:35.000 --> 06:39.300
science fiction conventions in the Southwest. It's held each year on the campus of Texas A&M

06:39.300 --> 06:44.020
University and is organized by the students at the university. Gordon Lewis, the head of the

06:44.020 --> 06:48.160
committee which is responsible for Aggicon, tells us what Aggicon has to offer a science fiction

06:48.160 --> 06:53.240
fan. There of course are the movies. I believe they have movies that are just about every

06:53.240 --> 06:59.080
science fiction convention. We have the dealer's room which you can find just about anything and

06:59.080 --> 07:07.500
everything in there from books to weapons to posters and other kind of paraphernalia from movies

07:07.500 --> 07:14.660
and the world of fantasy. We have the artists and the authors. They sit on panels, some of the

07:14.660 --> 07:23.040
authors do readings for us. We had a NASA presentation yesterday. We have had one of those

07:23.040 --> 07:29.780
for the past three years and we consider that to be pretty regular at this convention. We're

07:29.780 --> 07:36.800
having a slide show this afternoon on Don Penchot's artwork and we try to have an art slide show,

07:37.080 --> 07:42.880
or at least we've been trying to for the past three years. We have the two movie companies

07:42.880 --> 07:48.860
that are here, Disney and Columbia Pictures that are promoting films and I believe that since I've

07:48.860 --> 07:55.140
been here at Aggicon 12 I believe we didn't have any movie promotions but at 11 and 13 and at this

07:55.140 --> 08:02.000
one we have had movie promotions. We have trivia quizzes. We have the amateur art contest. We have

08:02.000 --> 08:08.140
the art auction as well as other stuff that's auctioned off. This year we had the world premiere

08:08.140 --> 08:13.000
performance of Mr. Harry Harrison's play. That is a first as far as I know.

08:15.960 --> 08:21.020
We also have the pro art gallery where pro artists can display their work and the fans can come and

08:21.020 --> 08:28.480
look at it. We have an autograph session, a guest reception. Plus you can usually find the guests

08:28.480 --> 08:31.240
down in the party room if they're not doing anything else.

08:46.460 --> 08:51.520
The authors at this year's Aggicon, the 14th, would have interested any science fiction fan.

08:52.100 --> 08:56.440
Harry Harrison was the guest of honor and there was also a special guest, Stephen R. Donaldson.

08:56.440 --> 09:00.620
Harrison has written science fiction for a long time and is known for such works as the

09:00.620 --> 09:04.840
Death World books and for the stainless steel rat novels. And Donaldson is one of the hottest

09:04.840 --> 09:09.380
fantasy authors working today. His two Chronicles of Thomas Covenant series have sold in the millions.

09:09.980 --> 09:13.820
Lewis says that this year's Aggicon gave more emphasis to one aspect of science fiction and

09:13.820 --> 09:18.520
fantasy that many casual readers don't give much thought to. This year we have really tried to

09:18.520 --> 09:23.500
do more stuff for the artists than we ever have in the past. Usually we have like one panel,

09:23.500 --> 09:29.120
the amateur art contest, the auction and that's about it. And this year we've programmed two panels

09:29.120 --> 09:36.580
on art. We again have the auction and the contest. We have more judges for the contest this year than

09:36.580 --> 09:42.320
we've had in the past. The artist guest of honor was Michael Whelan who for the past two years running

09:42.320 --> 09:45.620
has been given the Nebula Award as the best science fiction fantasy artist of the year.

09:46.060 --> 09:50.360
Anyone who reads science fiction has seen Whelan's work. His paintings are found on the covers of

09:50.360 --> 09:54.820
many science fiction and fantasy books. One of his latest creations was on the dust jacket of Arthur C.

09:55.060 --> 10:00.340
Clark's best-selling novel 2010 Odyssey 2. We asked Lewis how Aggicon compared with other

10:00.340 --> 10:05.860
science fiction conventions in Texas. Well we have been billed as the largest annual science

10:05.860 --> 10:12.860
fiction conventions so far as attendance is concerned. Overall I do believe that we have a

10:12.860 --> 10:18.600
larger attendance if you count both the one day passes as well as the full convention passes than

10:18.600 --> 10:23.540
what other science fiction conventions have. A lot of that is probably due to the students here on

10:23.540 --> 10:31.480
campus but we do bring in quite a few outside individuals. For instance this year we had

10:32.280 --> 10:37.180
60 non-student convention passes for the full convention that were sold in advance.

10:37.900 --> 10:42.680
That means before March 1st. We'll conclude our conversation with Gordon Lewis on our next show.

10:49.880 --> 10:54.720
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction

10:54.720 --> 10:58.540
Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

