This is the Science Fiction Radio Show so stay with us.

12:07.260 --> 12:12.540
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

12:15.240 --> 12:16.860
And here are your hosts.

12:21.060 --> 12:24.460
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. We are talking with Gordon Lewis,

12:24.760 --> 12:28.160
head of the Texas A&M Student Committee which put on this year's successful Aggicon.

12:28.700 --> 12:33.060
And this year's Aggicon the 14th has to be considered a success. The guest of honor was

12:33.060 --> 12:37.300
science fiction author Harry Harrison making one of his occasional trips to the United States from

12:37.300 --> 12:41.540
his home in Ireland. The special guest of honor was Stephen R. Donaldson, probably no fantasy

12:41.540 --> 12:45.860
author since Tolkien has sold more books than Donaldson has. His chronicles of Thomas Covenant

12:45.860 --> 12:50.540
one and two have sold in the millions. The activities at Aggicon 14 were numerous and

12:50.540 --> 12:54.780
fascinating. Fans could mingle with the authors and ask questions about their work for one thing

12:54.780 --> 12:58.020
and this opportunity would have to be the heart of any science fiction convention.

12:58.700 --> 13:04.560
But there was also a well-stocked dealer's room, movies 24 hours a day, panels, art shows, a masquerade,

13:04.960 --> 13:08.780
in other words an activity to give a fan a complete immersion in science fiction for almost

13:08.780 --> 13:13.100
four full days. We asked Gordon Lewis how they went about getting authors to be guests of Aggicon.

13:14.220 --> 13:19.000
Well usually what we like to do is there are some authors here in Texas as well as some artists

13:19.580 --> 13:23.240
who are kind of like traditionalists at Aggicon. They've been coming for several years.

13:23.960 --> 13:28.040
We try and invite all of them and usually most of them will come come down here.

13:29.040 --> 13:35.740
So far as our major guests we have the guest of honor and we have a special guest. This year

13:35.740 --> 13:40.040
we were going to have co-guests of honor. We were going to have Anne McCaffrey as well as Harry

13:40.040 --> 13:48.860
Harrison but Anne had to back out because of medical problems. Harry Harrison was then left as our

13:48.860 --> 13:53.540
only guest of honor which in the past we've only had one. We have our special guest like I said

13:53.540 --> 14:01.240
we have a toast master. This year is Dr. Chad Oliver from the University of Texas and he will

14:01.240 --> 14:06.240
be presenting a program at the banquet this evening. He said he'd give us 15 minutes of

14:06.240 --> 14:11.580
wit and humor. Chad Oliver has been writing science fiction for over 30 years and has been a regular

14:11.580 --> 14:16.300
feature at Aggicon. Some of the other local authors attending Aggicon 14 were Howard Waldrop,

14:16.620 --> 14:21.240
Lee Kennedy, Ardeth Mehar and George Proctor. The out-of-state writers included Ed Bryant and

14:21.240 --> 14:27.100
Bob Varterman. We asked Lewis what the biggest problem in planning Aggicon was. The fact that

14:27.100 --> 14:33.640
all of the officers are students and we all have our homework here from the University plus all

14:33.640 --> 14:39.340
of the paperwork that is required. And I think the only reason that was a real problem at this

14:39.340 --> 14:55.980
convention was because none of the paperwork was done when I took over in mid-October. I ended

14:55.980 --> 15:03.360
up in the middle of a school. Aggicon is put together by student committee at Texas A&M University

15:03.360 --> 15:07.200
known as Cepheid Variable. We wondered if the students joined the committee because they were

15:07.200 --> 15:13.980
serious science fiction fans are just for social reasons. Both really. The majority of the people

15:13.980 --> 15:19.080
in there are really interested in science fiction. I myself am very interested in science fiction and

15:19.080 --> 15:26.960
fantasy and it is a pretty nice social atmosphere also. The majority of the people in the committee

15:26.960 --> 15:32.280
are real good friends and we get along real well. How many students from Cepheid Variable work on

15:32.280 --> 15:39.800
the convention? We have our member right 16 officers, eight of those have assistants and we

15:39.800 --> 15:46.360
have probably 10 of what we termed gophers which means general officer for everything ridiculous.

15:47.540 --> 15:51.060
Basically they are the peons in your organization that go and do everything

15:51.640 --> 15:58.460
that the rest of us don't have time for. And then so far as workers at the convention, just general

15:58.460 --> 16:04.600
people, committee members that worked are probably another 10 to 20 of those. Lewis says the experience

16:04.600 --> 16:10.580
of putting on Aggicon is worthwhile but I would say that no one should criticize the way a science

16:10.580 --> 16:16.640
fiction fantasy convention is run until they've been on my end of the deal. Because until you have

16:16.640 --> 16:20.920
tried to set one of these things up you really don't have any understanding as to what it takes to do

16:20.920 --> 16:29.080
so. All of the paperwork and all of the correspondence that has to be done. It really is a very big job

16:29.080 --> 16:32.380
and I'm sure that this year I could not have done it without the help of all my officers.

16:38.760 --> 16:44.140
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction

16:44.140 --> 16:47.960
Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

